<div class="container-fluid" id="faq">
<h2 class="text-center">Autism FAQ</h2>
<div class="row">
		<div class= "col-sm-3 col-icon">
			<span class="glyphicon glyphicon-question-sign"></span>
		</div>
		<div class="col-md-3 col-sm-4 col-xs-12">
			<h4>What is autism?</h4>
			Autism is a spectrum of neurological differences that affects approximately one percent of the population.
			<h4>Do all autistic people share the same characteristics?</h4>
			No, autism manifests itself differently in each individual. However, many (not all) autistic people share the following characteristics to some degree:
			<ul>
			<li>Sensory differences</li>
			<li>Difficulty with social skills and communication</li>
			<li>Executive functioning differences</li>
			<li>Need for routine</li>
			<li>Special interests</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
		<div class="col-md-3 col-sm-4 col-xs-12">
			<h4>Do vaccines cause autism?</h4>
			No, there is <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/vaccinesafety/concerns/autism.html">no link between vaccines and autism</a>. In fact, many autistic people feel that the anti-vax movement creates unneccessary fearmongering regarding autism.
			<h4>Can autistic people live a normal life?</h4>
			Absolutely! While autistic adults and young people may need support to some degree, many autistic people go on to college and/or the workplace. It has even been suggested that <a href="https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn3676-einstein-and-newton-showed-signs-of-autism">some of history's greatest scientists showed signs of autism</a>.
		</div>
		<div class="col-md-3 col-sm-4 col-xs-12">
			<h4>Person-first or identity-first language?</h4>
			Many people with disabilities prefer "person-first" language, putting the person before the disability, e.g."person with disability". This website primarily uses identity-first language because many people in the Autistic community believe that autism is part of their identity.
			<h4>I've been told autism is overdiagnosed/part of a government conspiracy- is that true?</h4>
			No, doctors have just been getting better at identifying signs of autism. Any "conspiracy" stems from ignorance. Don't believe everything you read on the Internet!
		</div>
</div>
</div>
